Component Development & Prototypes (ACD&P)
 systems. FF(X) addition of the flexible weapons station facilitates loadout of containerized payloads, the same payloads as Medium Unmanned Surface Vessel (MUSV)
 can carry, and ultimately enabling associated benefits of scalable technology, rapid and cost-effective innovation, and tailored missions through containerized missiles
 or other weapons systems. This approach provides an inherent growth path for VLS and other capabilities through containerized solutions in early flights, reinforcing the
 platform's adaptability while mitigating cost, schedule, and integration risks associated with fixed VLS installation.

Combat system development activities focus on integration and verification of key sensors and weapons, including Atalanta Combat System (CS), SPS-77 radar,
Mk48 Mod 2 Gun Weapon System, and Rolling Airframe Missile (RAM). Efforts include hardware and software integration, interface definition, and validation of system
performance within the platform's warfare architecture. The program supports development of an integrated warfare system baseline, ensuring interoperability across
combat, C4I, and aviation domains and enabling effective response to current and emerging threats.

RDTE funding supports risk reduction through system-level integration, collaborative design efforts with the shipbuilder and stakeholders, land-based and ship-based
test planning, and preparation for developmental and operational test events. Activities include maturation of system interfaces, validation of combat system functionality,
and integration of unmanned system command and control capabilities. Studies conducted under this effort will inform future capability increments and flight upgrades,
including transition from Atalanta Weapon System to ICS, incorporation of future RAS C2 elements, potential integration of Vertical Launch Systems (VLS) and Anti-
Submarine Warfare (ASW) systems in follow-on flights. The program maintains a development schedule aligned to launch of the lead ship in 2028.

Early investment in design completion, integration, and test planning reduces technical and schedule risk and supports a transition to production. Additionally, future
RDTE funding will develop integration of unmanned assets such as Medium Unmanned Surface Vessel (MUSV) into the FF(X) kill chain. FF(X) will team with and
quarterback MUSVs across all domains. These unmanned assets will function as extensions, or in addition to, FF(X)'s own sensors and weapons providing persistent
capabilities in early warning, Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance (ISR), communications, and offensive strikes. This integration enhances the common
operating picture and supports integrated fire control solutions, enabling a distributed and more lethal force.

