1319 / 4                                              PE 0603609N / Conventional Munitions    0364 / Explosives S$$, $$851ff7a1841b8326eb8ba2e6ee1a66aa1be2a81839dc98de0e7d16c2a950b4de$$, $${"A": "c0c1afd7a734200959ba5d948bc7c73273d3dca4e4fff54cbef7d84d861e970f", "C": "d4fdf923ba776b98bda680220afe7660b2fb7f78e25f4cb026ad0b29031d9620", "D": "e1365f85a3b32440380e9ac26cb8289cb0acececacdd72d6597bfec7610844d3"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY27/Navy/RDTEN_BA4_Book.pdf$$, 757, $$2026-05-10T04:04:19.242458+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0603635M$$, 2027, $$This PE is fundamentally a crucial "try before you buy" initiative for the Marine Corps' entire arsenal of ground combat and fire support systems. Its core purpose is to
rigorously test, experiment with, and ultimately validate new or upgraded weapons and equipment in the most realistic scenarios possible before the Corps commits to
a massive investment in full-scale production and fielding. This meticulous process ensures that every piece of gear eventually placed into the hands of a Marine is not
only lethal and effective but also entirely reliable and perfectly suited for their unique mission, thereby safeguarding lives and taxpayer dollars by preemptively avoiding
costly failures.

Focus on the formal "Demonstration and Validation" phase within the military acquisition lifecycle. This stage, arriving after initial concepts and foundational technologies
have been explored but before a commitment to mass procurement, is designed to reduce inherent risks. It seeks definitive answers to critical questions: Does this new
weapon system truly perform as its manufacturer claims? Can our Marines effectively operate and maintain it under the severe stress of a combat environment? Will it
seamlessly integrate with our existing communication networks, targeting equipment, and other systems? Ultimately, this is the "prove it to me" phase, where this PE
funds the necessary activities to secure that undeniable proof.

The scope of this funding is directed precisely at Marine Corps Ground and Supporting Arms Systems. This means it explicitly covers the direct combat tools of our
infantry and combat support units, such as new rifles, machine guns, or anti-tank weapons, alongside the systems that provide crucial indirect fire support, including
advanced artillery, rocket systems like HIMARS, and the sophisticated fire control technology that ensures their pinpoint accuracy.

Crucially, all this testing and validation is focused on their utilization within Marine Air-Ground Task Force (MAGTF) amphibious operations - the signature mission of
the Marine Corps. This context is paramount, as it defines the specific, unforgiving environment where these systems must not only function but excel. Amphibious
operations introduce unique challenges: can the equipment withstand corrosive saltwater spray and fine sand? Can it be easily and robustly transported on landing craft,
helicopters, or amphibious vehicles through rough seas and onto a contested beach? Is it durable enough to survive such transit and still perform? Does it fit within the
limited confines of a naval vessel or an amphibious vehicle, and can it be maintained in an austere environment with minimal logistical support? A weapon that performs
 flawlessly on a controlled test range might catastrophically fail during a real-world beach landing; this PE funds the vital testing to uncover such vulnerabilities before
 lives are on the line.

This program prioritizes the development and integration of actual hardware for these experimental tests. This isn't merely about theoretical reports or computer
simulations. Instead, this funding is directly used to build production-representative prototypes, integrate them with existing Marine Corps gear to ensure interoperability,
and then put them through rigorous, live-fire exercises and simulated amphibious landings in the hands of Marines. Through these essential, hands-on, hardware-
focused experiments, the Marine Corps gathers the empirical data needed to make informed, sound decisions on whether to proceed with a major acquisition, ultimately
ensuring our warfighters are equipped with nothing but the best.

The FY 2026 spend plan amount for Combat Capability Development Transition Long Range Unmanned Surface Vessels (LRUSV) includes $23,793 thousands of
discretionary and $4,750 thousands of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $28,543 thousands.$$, $$The Marine Corps is establishing a new Maritime Reconnaissance Company (MRC) unit as part of the broader evolution of our light armored reconnaissance (LAR)
battalions into mobile reconnaissance battalions (MRBs). The MRC will operate a new tactical boat, the Multi-Mission Reconnaissance Craft (MMRC), which can partner
with unmanned systems to maneuver sensors and personnel in support of Marine forces operating in the littorals.

Long Range Unmanned Surface Vessel (LRUSV) was an unmanned, semi-autonomous platform capable of multi-domain sensor collections that enabled the
Marine Littoral Regiment / Marine Expeditionary Force to enhance Maritime Domain Awareness (MDA) for the Joint Force. LRUSV employed a suite of organic
sensors (RADAR, EO/IR, and Electromagnetic Support) to accomplish its primary function of gaining and maintaining custody of surface contacts of interest in the
littoral operating environment. LRUSV sensor capabilities assisted the Marine Division's Maritime Reconnaissance Company in its mission to conduct seaward
Reconnaissance, Surveillance, and Target Acquisition (RSTA) in a peer-threat contested, littoral operating environment across the spectrum of competition, crisis, and
conflict to enhance Joint and coalition MDA and facilitate the application of organic and Joint fires.

Multi-Mission Reconnaissance Craft (MMRC) is a manned vessel, which when teamed with unmanned systems, will enable the stand-in force to use the sea as
maneuver space, exploiting the predominate terrain in the littoral environment to extend their RSTA capabilities beyond the limitations of land-based systems. The
capability will provide a persistent, fused, all weather maritime domain awareness collections capability that enables over-the-horizon (OTH) targeting and facilitates
the application of organic and Joint fires. Additionally, the MMRC will insert and extract teams across challenging open water distances, emplace/recover sensors, and
provide a stable, protected platform to maneuver specialist capabilities to seaward.

In FY 2026, LRUSV implemented and completed sensor enhancements, conducted smaller form factor USV developmental testing, and completed facilities studies.
Based on the completion of the LRUSV effort, in FY 2027 the Marine Corps is shifting focus to a manned MMRC platform.

