 limited confines of a naval vessel or an amphibious vehicle, and can it be maintained in an austere environment with minimal logistical support? A weapon that performs
 flawlessly on a controlled test range might catastrophically fail during a real-world beach landing; this PE funds the vital testing to uncover such vulnerabilities before
 lives are on the line.

This program prioritizes the development and integration of actual hardware for these experimental tests. This isn't merely about theoretical reports or computer
simulations. Instead, this funding is directly used to build production-representative prototypes, integrate them with existing Marine Corps gear to ensure interoperability,
and then put them through rigorous, live-fire exercises and simulated amphibious landings in the hands of Marines. Through these essential, hands-on, hardware-
focused experiments, the Marine Corps gathers the empirical data needed to make informed, sound decisions on whether to proceed with a major acquisition, ultimately
ensuring our warfighters are equipped with nothing but the best.

The FY 2026 spend plan amount for Combat Capability Development Transition Long Range Unmanned Surface Vessels (LRUSV) includes $23,793 thousands of
discretionary and $4,750 thousands of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $28,543 thousands.

