FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Through leveraging new technologies, NAVSUP will enhance efforts for digital transformation of logistics
services, sailor uniform innovations, and supply ashore. NAVSUP will collaborate with partners to improve the
quality-of-life experiences and expand services to deployed forces. NAVSUP will pivot towards modernizing
Sailor uniforms (Clothing Protection for the Warfighter) to meet the expectations of modern warfare and restoring
Warrior Ethos.
Title: Clothing Protection for the Warfighter                                                                              0.630      0.505       0.929      0.000        0.929
                                                                                                           Articles:          -          -           -          -            -
Description: Identify challenges to effectively manage durability and safety aspects of common work/combat
uniforms for the warfighter. Eliminate risk of hazardous factors such as fire, weather, and general wear/tear to
maximize readiness and strength in Fleet uniforms. Assist with specifications associated with permanent press
finish related to the rollout of the Navy's Type III uniform.

FY 2026 Plans:
Validate data from assessment of the Effect of Women Specific Sizing on Clothing System Performance
($100K): Validate the data established in FY25 initiative using SHEMO thermal manikin and female flame
manikin, respectively. Correlation between manikins is required as to ascertain and be effective in the use of
evaluation system performance. This effort will expand the developments from FY24.

Footwear Protection Market Research ($50K): The need for additional footwear suppliers has become a concern
over the past few years due to various factory closures, etc. At this time there is limited information as to the
potential to understand and establish the "best fit" for footwear. As well as supply base in limited in one supplier
for steel and composite protection. This effort will follow-on efforts that the Army is taking on as it aligns with
footwear improvement for the future.

Product Lifecycle Management ($170K): Finalize the establishment of this automated platform for clothing and
textiles. Document the operation parameters to transition to sustainment support. Quantify costs for out years to
maintain this platform for the future. Aligns with Joint Clothing Textile Modernization Initiative.

Modernized Materials for Dress Clothing ($60K): Are there alternative fabrics that can be used in dress clothing
that provide superior quality at comparable price points? Elastomeric material is the go-to fiber for dress clothing
for its ability to give with wear but quantification of the use of elastomerics use in dress clothing is necessary.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions, Article Quantities in Each)                                                              FY 2027    FY 2027      FY 2027
                                                                                                                         FY 2025   FY 2026    Base       OOC          Total

Navy Organizational Clothing Size Standardization ($75K): Based on the data gathered from FY25 efforts
to understand the methods and approach to implementation of Block patterns for ORG clothing. Establish a
framework for implementation of this research and approach socialization with Navy Protective Clothing Board
on means and methods of the use of blocks as it aligns with General Purpose Organizational Clothing.

Analysis of Fiber Fragmentation (AATCC TM212) ($50K): With the recent interest in the concern of PFAS
in clothing and textiles as well as the impact of laundering items containing PFAS, NCTRF will investigate
AATCC TM212 Analysis of Fiber Fragmentation. When clothing and textiles are laundered, fiber fragments come
off. Most fragments are not filtered out from water effluent and end up in the waterways and ecosystems. To
reduce the negative environmental impact, NCTRF proposes to evaluate ways to quantify and minimize fiber
fragmentation and improve filtration of fiber fragments from washing machine effluent. This research will look at
which fabrics have the least fragmentation and recommend material changes for garments currently made from
fabrics with high amounts of fiber fragmentation.
FY 2027 Base Plans:
Shipboard Cold Weather Clothing (CWC) R&D Recommendations and transition (110K): The effort will work
synergistically with the Navy General Purpose Organizational Clothing Size Standardization and Performance
Impact Assessment. Establish a recommendation for adoption and usage of the CWC Shipboard uniform
system.

Specific Sizing on Clothing System Performance Data Assessment (69K):
This test plan outlines an approach to validate data from the SHEMO thermal manikin and the flame
manikin, establishing a correlation between their results. The plan involves coordination with academic and
industry partners and the utilization of in-house data to understand the impact of body forms on system-level
performance.

Footwear Protection Market Research (40K):
This plan outlines a strategy to address the limited number of footwear suppliers and the lack of a standardized
"best fit" methodology. The approach is aligned with ongoing Army efforts to improve footwear for the future, with
a specific focus on the critical need for additional suppliers of steel and composite protection.

Product Lifecycle Management (550K): Implementation of a digital engineering platform for clothing and textiles.
This system will streamline operations as well as build efficiencies and provide a digital repository for the future.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions, Article Quantities in Each)                                                              FY 2027     FY 2027     FY 2027
                                                                                                                       FY 2025    FY 2026     Base        OOC         Total
NAVSUP will build Navy requirements and implement framework. Additionally, quantify management costs for
out-years to maintain this platform and refinement of standardized processes for use.

Assessment to refine approaches with made to measure and special measurements (60K): The project will
collect data from an assessment of Navy clothing & textile (C&T) procurement and changing the processes for
the MTM and special measurements. This effort will align with size modernization tools and streamline approach
and implement a clear process for usage.

Natural Fibers efforts and alignment with modernization of clothing & textile items (100K): Develop a catalog of
new materials available for developmental items. Previous research identified several items that have strong
potential for use. Ongoing research will expand that catalog. For each item, suggested use cases and limitations
to adoption will also be produced. Locate alternative fabric sources that can be used to modernize dress or utility
clothing items. Utilize information from service life development to baseline a level of performance.
